
Sysmon (System Monitor)

Sysmon is a Windows system service that provides enhanced security logging beyond default Windows Event Logs.
It is widely used by SOC analysts for monitoring process execution, network activity, and system changes.


---

Downloading Sysmon

Sysmon was downloaded manually using a web browser from the official Microsoft Sysinternals website.

Steps followed:

Opened a web browser

Navigated to the Microsoft Sysinternals Sysmon download page

Downloaded Sysmon64.exe for a 64-bit Windows system

Saved the file locally (e.g., C:\Sysmon)



---

Installing Sysmon

Sysmon was installed using Administrator privileges.

Sysmon64.exe -i sysmonconfig.xml

This command:

Installed Sysmon as a Windows service

Applied the XML configuration file

Began logging security events immediately



---

Configuring Sysmon

Sysmon configuration was done using an XML configuration file to control what events are logged and reduce noise.

The configuration enabled logging for:

Process creation

Network connections

File creation

Registry modifications

DNS queries


Configuration updates were applied without reinstalling Sysmon:

Sysmon64.exe -c sysmonconfig.xml


---

Key Sysmon Event IDs

Event ID	Description

1	Process creation
3	Network connection
11	File creation
13	Registry modification
22	DNS query



---

Log Location

Sysmon events are stored in:

Event Viewer →
Applications and Services Logs →
Microsoft →
Windows →
Sysmon →
Operational


---

SOC Relevance

Sysmon provides high-quality telemetry used for threat detection, incident investigation, and SIEM monitoring.

